Negotiating hearing disability and hearing disabled identities.

Hindhede AL(1).

Author information:
(1)University of Aarhus, Denmark. anlh@dpu.dk

Using disability theory as a framework and social science theories of identity 
to strengthen the arguments, this article explores empirically how working-age 
adults confront the medical diagnosis of hearing impairment. For most 
participants hearing impairment threatens the stability of social interaction 
and the construction of hearing disabled identities is seen as shaped in the 
interaction with the hearing impaired person's surroundings. In order to 
overcome the potential stigmatization the 'passing' as normal becomes 
predominant. For many the diagnosis provokes radical redefinitions of the self. 
The discursively produced categorization and subjectivity of senescence mean 
that rehabilitation technologies such as hearing aids identify a particular 
life-style (disabled) which determines their social significance. Thus wearing a 
hearing aid works against the contemporary attempt to create socially ideal 
bodily presentations of the self, as the hearing aid is a symbolic extension of 
the body's lack of function.

DOI: 10.1177/1363459311403946
PMID: 21540252 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


